<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41043c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41043c">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41043c"> 43(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> infeft</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Courtesy is the life-rent of the whole of the wife&apos;s heritable estate in Scotland, which is enjoyed by the husband on her death if there was a child of the marriage. These conditions are requisite before the husband is entitled to this life-rent: (I) the wife must have died <mark>infeft</mark>: (2) a child which has been heard to cry must have been born, and (3) this child must be the wife&apos;s heir. Note: Infeft. In Scottish law, invested with heritable property. <small> Maud I. Crofts, <a name="MICW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MICW"><cite title="source">Women under English Law</cite></a>, 1st ed. (1925) 94</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
